definition.value: A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 55 carbons and 10 double bonds.
A triglyceride in which the three acyl groups contain a total of 58 carbons and 11 double bonds.
A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of 6-methylpretetramide, obtained by deprotonation of the 1-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).

A phenolate anion that is the conjugate base of 4-hydroxy-6-methylpretetramide, obtained by deprotonation of the 1-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An N-acyl-L-alanine resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of L-alanine with the carboxy group of (12S)-hydroperoxy-(5Z,8Z,10E,14Z)-icosatetraenoic acid.

An organic anion that is the conjugate base of 4-dedimethylamino-4-oxoanhydrotetracycline, obtained by deprotonation of the 2-hydroxy group. It is the major microspecies at pH 7.3 (according to Marvin v 6.2.0.).
An N-acylglycine resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of glycine with the carboxy group of (15S)-hydroperoxy-(5Z,8Z,11Z,13E)-icosatetraenoic acid.
A phthalic acid monoester resulting from the formal condensation of one of the carboxy groups of phthalic acid with the alcoholic hydroxy group of 8-hydroxyoctanoic acid.
An N-acyl-amino acid resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of gamma-aminobutyric acid with the carboxy group of (12S)-hydroperoxy-(5Z,8Z,10E,14Z)-icosatetraenoic acid.
A lysophosphatidylglycerol in which the acyl group has a fully saturated C13 chain and is attached to the glycero moiety at either position 1 or 2.
A member of the class of lysophosphatidic acids obtained by hydrolytic removal of one of the two acyl groups of any phosphatidic acid. A 'closed' class.
A lysophosphatidic acid in which the acyl group (position not specified) contains 14 carbons and no double bonds.
A lysophosphatidic acid in which the acyl group (position not specified) contains 16 carbons and no double bonds.
A lysophosphatidic acid in which the acyl group (position not specified) contains 18 carbons and no double bonds.
An N-acyl-L-alanine resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of L-alanine with the carboxy group of (15S)-hydroperoxy-(5Z,8Z,11Z,13E)-icosatetraenoic acid.

An N-acyl-gamma-aminobutyric acid resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of gamma-aminobutyric acid with the carboxy group of (15S)-hydroperoxy-(5Z,8Z,11Z,13E)-icosatetraenoic acid.
An organic sodium salt resulting from the replacement of the proton from the carboxy group of vanillic acid by a sodium ion.
A berberine alkaloid that is 5,8,13,13a-tetrahydro-2H,6H-[1,3]dioxolo[4,5-g]isoquinolino[3,2-a]isoquinoline carrying hydroxy and methoxy substituents at positions 9 and 10 respectively.
A tertiary alcohol that is propan-1-ol in which both of the hydrogens at position 1 have been replaced by methyl groups.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of thiamine hydrochloride.
A tertiary alcohol that is 3-methylbut-1-ene carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 3.
A hydrochloride obtained by combining triethanolamine with one equivalent of hydrogen chloride.

A carbohydrazide resulting from the formal condensation of the hydrazone moiety of 3,4-dihydroxybenzaldehyde hydrazone with the carboxy group of 3-hydroxy-2-naphthoic acid. It is a cell-permeable, reversible noncompetitive inhibitor of the GTPase activity of dynamin 1 and 2 and Drp1 (mitochondrial), while exhibiting no significant effect against two other small GTPases, MxA and Cdc42.
An organic cation obtained by protonation of the tertiary amino group of triethanolamine.
A member of the class of glycerophosphoglycerols that is sn-glycero-3-phosphoglycerol carrying an unspecified alkyl substituent at position 1
A member of the class of glycerophosphoglycerols that is sn-glycero-3-phosphoglycerol carrying an unspecified Z-alk-1-enyl substituent at position 1
A vanadyl sulfate hydrate containing five water molecules.
A 1-alkyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoglycerol in which the alkyl group contains 34 carbons and 4 double bonds.
A 1-(Z-alk-1-enyl)-sn-glycero-3-phosphoglycerol in which the alkenyl group contains 34 carbons and has 3 additional double bonds.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion in which the acyl groups at C-1 and C-2 contain 40 carbons in total with 6 double bonds and 1 hydroxy substituent.
A hydrate that is the hexahydrate form of zinc sulfate.
Any polyunsaturated fatty acid containing 19 carbons and 5 double bonds.
An organic sodium salt consisting of sodium and oxalate ions in a 2:1 ratio.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of sodium metavanadate.
An organic sodium salt composed of sodium and nitrilotriacetate ions in a 3:1 ratio.
An iron coordination entity composed from Fe(3+) cations and diphosphate(4-) anions in a 4:3 ratio.

A member of the class of coumarins that is 7-methoxycoumarin in which the hydrogen at position 6 has been replaced by a 1-ethoxy-2,3-dihydroxy-3-methylbutyl group (the R,R stereoisomer). Originally isolated from the roots of Angelica pubescens, angelol J shows strong inhibitory effects on human platelet aggregation.
An inorganic sodium salt that has fluorate as the counter-ion.
A triacylglycerol 52:3 in which the acyl groups at positions 1, 2 and 3 are specified as palmitoyl, linoleoyl and oleoyl respectively.

label.value: EC 3.6.5.* (hydrolases acting on GTP; involved in cellular and subcellular movement) inhibitor

definition.value: Any EC 3.6.* (hydrolases acting on acid anhydrides) inhibitor that interferes with the action of any such enzyme acting on GTP that is involved in cellular and subcellular movement (EC 3.6.5.*).
An EC 3.6.5.* (hydrolases acting on GTP; involved in cellular and subcellular movement) inhibitor that interferes with the action of dynamin GTPase (EC 3.6.5.5).
A triglyceride having stearoyl (octadecanoyl) groups at positions 1 and 3 and a palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) group at position 2. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

An N-acylglycine resulting from the formal condensation of the amino group of glycine with the carboxy group of 4-hydroxy-1-methyl-7-phenoxyisoquinoline-3-carboxylic acid. It is an inhibitor of hypoxia inducible factor prolyl hydroxylase (HIF-PH).

A triacylglycerol 50:1 in which the acyl groups at positions 1, 2 and 3 are specified as oleoyl, isoheptadecanoyl and pentadecanoyl respectively.  It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

A triacylglycerol 52:1 in which the acyl groups at positions 1, 2 and 3 are specified as oleoyl, isononadecanoyl and pentadecanoyl respectively. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

A triacylglycerol 50:2 in which the acyl groups at positions 1, 2 and 3 are specified as linoleoyl, isoheptadecanoyl and isopentadecanoyl respectively. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

A triacylglycerol 50:2 in which the acyl groups at positions 1, 2 and 3 are specified as linoleoyl, oleoyl and isoheptadecanoyl respectively. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

A beta-D-glucosylceramide in which a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached to the primary hydroxyl group of N-docosanoyl-14-methylhexadecasphingosine. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

A beta-D-glucosylceramide in which a beta-D-glucosyl residue attached to the primary hydroxyl group of N-tricosanoyl-14-methylhexadecasphingosine. It is a metabolite of the nematode Caenorhabditis elegans.

A sulfonamide resulting from the formal condensation of the sulfonic acid group of 5-(dimethylamino)naphthalene-1-sulfonic acid with the aniline nitrogen of 3-(2-acetamido-1,3-thiazol-4-yl)aniline. It has been reported that by triggering an  endoplasmic reticulum (ER) stress response, HA15 can reduce the viability of melanoma cells without being toxic to normal cells.
